L-v-m operations: resize, snapshots, and extend.

Resizing a logical volume is the whole reason l-v-m exists, so let us see it clearly. Growing a volume is really two steps: enlarge the logical volume, then enlarge the filesystem sitting on it. The l-v-extend command does the first, and with the dash r flag it does the second in the same breath, growing the underlying filesystem for you. You can grow by a relative amount, set an absolute new size, or tell it to take all the remaining free space in the pool. That dash r flag is the magic; without it you would have to call a separate filesystem-resize tool yourself afterward.

Shrinking is the harder, riskier direction, and a key fact to remember is that only e-x-t-four can shrink; x-f-s can never be made smaller. To shrink e-x-t-four you must work in the opposite order: unmount it, run a forced filesystem check, shrink the filesystem first with the resize tool, then shrink the logical volume to match, and remount. Because it is risky, back up before shrinking. The takeaway: growing is the l-v-m superpower, so prefer it whenever you can.

Two more operations complete the toolkit. When the whole pool runs low, you extend the volume group by preparing a new partition as a physical volume and adding it with v-g-extend, which gives you more free space to grow volumes into. And snapshots are instant, space-efficient point-in-time copies of a logical volume, made with l-v-create and the snapshot flag. A snapshot is itself a block device, so you can mount it read-only and back it up calmly while the original keeps serving traffic, then remove the snapshot when you are done. Snapshots are perfect for taking a consistent backup of a live system, or for giving yourself a rollback point before a risky change.
